Email Security


# Email Headers
  ## SSMTP.mailfrom (P1 Sender)
    Technical sender address
    P1 sender (the REAL sender)
    The address mail servere verify
  ## From (P2 Sender)
    The visible sender address seen by users
    aka P2 sender
    Weakness: can be easily spoofed by attackers
  ## Authentication Results
     Contains email authentication results
     Shows whether SPF, DKIM, and DMARC checks passed or failed

# Email Authentication Checks
  ## Sender Policy Framework (SPF)
    Verifies that the sending mail server is authorized by the domain
    Uses DNS records to validate sender IP
    If SPF fails:
    THe Sending server isn't approvged by the domain
    Possible spoofing attempt
  ## DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM)
    Uses asymmetric encry[tion to verify email integrity
    Public key is stored in the domain's DNS records
    If DKIM fails:
    The email may have been tampered with
    Signature verification failed
  ## Domain-based MEssage Authentication, Reporting, and Conformance (DMARC)
    Validates alignment between P1 (SMTP.mailfrom) and P2 (From)
    If DMARC fails:
    High likelihood of email spoofing

# Phishing
  Phishing is the act of sending fraudulent emails pretending to be legitimate to steal information or gain access.
    ## Types
    Spear Phishing - Targeted at specific person or company
    Whaling - targets high-level individuals (CEO, admin)
    Smishing - Phising via text
    Vishing - Phishing via phone calls

# Credential Harvesting
  Emails designed to trick users into entering login credentials (often via fake login pages)
    ## Indicators
    Newly registered domains (< 1 month old)
    Broken or sus URLs (e.g., 404 pages)
    Login requests outside trusted platforms
    ## Mitigations
    Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
    Data Loss Prevention (DLP) policies
    Domain blocklists

# Malware Delivery
  Emails designed to get users to execute malicious code
  ## Common Delivery Methods
  File-sharing links
  Attachments
  multi-stage downloads
  User-triggered execution
  ## Indicators
  Unknown processes running
  Apps like Word or Chrome spawning PowerShell or cmd.exe
  Suspicious outbound network traffic after interaction
  Antivirus alerts in mail client

# Social Engineering
  Manipulating users into performing harmful actions
  ## Examples
  Phishing for sensitive info
  Business Email Compromise (BEC)
  Unauthorized wire transfers
  Data exfiltration
  ## Indicators
  Spoofed P2 sender
  Failed SPF/DKIM checks
  Unknown or suspicious sender domains
  Suspicious subject lines or email content
  ## Mitigations
  Employee security training
  Assume emails are malicious until proven benign

  # Social Engineering Detection
    ## Psychological Tactics Used
    Authority - pretending to be a boss or trusted entity
    INtimidation - threats if action is not taken
    urgency - pressure to act quickly
    ## Red Flags
    Inconsistend or unnatural language
    Overly polite or generic greetings
    Spelling and grammar mistakes
    Missing email signature
    Use of personal info to build trust
  # Recon / Test Enumeration
    Often overlooked attack type
      Emails designed to confirm a target existss and will respond
      Goal is not immediate harm, but furure exploitation
      *Can lead to more advanced phishing or attacks later
  # General Email Security Principle
  Eamils w/o clear malicious goal aren't automatically safe
  can be:
    spam
    Marketing
  If unsure:
    Categorize as undetermined
    Escalate to more expereinced analyst
# Indicators of Email Compromise
  ## Suspicious Behavior
  Strange inbox rules
  Mass email sending or deletion
  Large file downloads or charing activity
  ## Account Activity
  Unusual sign-in attempts
  Multiple authentication events across services
  Logins from unfamiliar locations
  
    
